<div class=row>
  <section class="built-it-no-one-came">
    <div>
      <h2 class="centered">Built It But No-one Came?</h2>
      <p>
        <b>Online marketing is the killer skill in today's world, </b>yet it is seldom taught. Indeed, many find it distasteful. Just as elite universities shun teaching it, smart students avoid learning it, eager to believe that their own brilliance will carry the day; that if they build themselves up, success will inevitably come.</p>

      <p><b>But this is a fairy tale: mediocre people and mediocre products often out-compete and out-sell their superiors thanks to marketing chops.</b> (Ahem, Microsoft.) If you want success in today's attention starved world, you need to know how to reach people. It's not enough to sit back in your safe space and hope things will work out...
      </p>

      <p><b>This book doesn't cover all online marketing activities: it focuses on building scalable, automatable "marketing assets", bits and pieces that continue to bring traffic dividends long into the future.</b> If we're going to throw around keywords, this book is about search engine optimisation, paid advertising, conversion optimisation, auto-email marketing, and copywriting. Anything requiring continuous attention didn't make the cut. Sorry, social media marketing.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>

<div class=row>
  <section class="benefits-of-reading">
    <h2 class="centered">The Key Benefits</h2>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="benefits-of-reading__traffic">
        <h3>Get More Traffic, Money, Recognition, and Even Free Time</h3>
        <p>Let's not beat around the bush here: the main reason to read this book is increase traffic. Whether you are seeking riches, recognition, reform, or repose, traffic is the crucial first step in today's internet-addicted world. Now that the ability to get published has been fully democratised through Web 2.0 technologies, attention has become the world's scarcest resource. And as with any other scarce resource, whoever has it gains the power to do whatever they please. It is the well-known who will inherit the earth..</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="benefits-of-reading__universal-principles">
        <%= image_tag("") %>
        <h3>Universal Marketing Principles Instead of the Nitty-Gritty</h3>
        <p>
          The only constant in the internet age is change. That's why the wisest career-minded people specialise on the timeless rather than the transient. <i><%= book.title %></i> leaves out the minutiae of configuring advertising software or setting up Google Analytics: this sort of tedium changes every six months and you might as well Google the official docs. In place of this trivia, this book focuses on the evergreen, on showing you the lay of the land, and on instilling the strategic principles that will keep paying dividends for years and years and years to come.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="benefits-of-reading__dangerous">
        <h3>Know Enough To Be Dangerous After Only 10 Hours</h3>
        <p>If this is your first serious online marketing read, you'll leave the book with a newfound ability to concoct clever marketing strategies that'll make your co-workers, co-founders, and clients raise their eyebrows in intrigue and empower you to switch on a fire hose of traffic to your web properties. Obviously, you won't be a master of marketing after reading this, but you will know your way around the ecosystem. And with a little practice the ideas in this book will gradually become internalised, automatic, and second nature to you.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="benefits-of-reading__concrete-examples">
        <h3>Packed with Real-World, Concrete Examples</h3>
        <p>This book was written by a marketer who got down and dirty building his own businesses, someone who kept his ears to the ground and his eyes open. You won't find any highfalutin academic theories or armchair punditry here; instead this is a practical and empirical book, based on observations from the field and trial and error. Everything you read here will be accompanied by examples and placed in a practical context which you can easily translate back to your own marketing problems.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="benefits-of-reading__crammed-advice">
        <h3>A Book That Respects Your Time</h3>
        <p>The overwhelming majority of business/sales/marketing books contain about 10 pages of content for every 200 pages of unnecessary, condescending, repetitive filler. Traditional publishers insist on padding out their books and bumping up the page count, even when the authors of these books don't have an awful lot to say... By contrast, this book squeezes and condenses the world of online marketing into a concentrated and interconnected whole that respects your time and intelligence. This is the perfect guide for busy people who want the maximum rate of information intake per second. If Tim Ferris wrote a marketing book...
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>

<div class="row">
  <section class="what-you-learn">
    <h2 class="centered">A Taster of What You'll Learn</h2>
    <div class="row">
      <div class="half-page">
        <h3>Paid Advertising</h3>
        <ul class="benefits-list">
          <li><b>The 8 best categories of photos for sticking in your online advertisements</b>. To give one example: anthropomorphic food. You wouldn't believe how often people click on cappuccinos with smiley faces or cupcakes with legs. I wish I was joking... </li>
          <li>Why advertisers are so excited about <b>behaviour targeting, the latest (and scariest) generation of online advertising technologies </b>that let you target people based on their <i>real world</i> behaviours (e.g. "bought peanut butter in the store", "owns a car", "is an expat", etc.)</li>
          <li><b>How to spot promising niches for new/related products through "advertising ease" research. </b>This is a damn lot cheaper than developing a product first, only to realise nobody wants it. This is the Lean Startup-lite.</li>
          <li>The cunning to <b>recognise the lies lurking behind the many feel-good metrics given in paid advertising reports. A great click-through rate may hide the fact that none of those clickers every bought something from you.</b> A great conversion rate may hide the fact that the people who converted only bought your lowest-margin products.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Statistical Significance Testing</h3>
        <ul class="benefits-list">
          <li>The real world concerns of statistical significance, that old epistemological bugbear that, when left unchecked, can quickly lead you up the garden path when trying to improve your on-site (and off-site) conversion rates. <b>Instead of diving too deep into the math, the book will keep you intrigued with examples from politics polling and mobile-phone cancer linkage research.</b> The section concludes with practical pointers.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Google Analytics</h3>
        <ul class="benefits-list">
          <li>How to integrate analytical and tracking systems that tell you whether your paid advertising campaigns are worth keeping around. These reports should be sophisticated enough to take into account unavoidable expenses like sales tax, shipping fees, and costs of merchandise. <b>Revenue is for losers; you want profit.</b></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Email Marketing</h3>
        <ul class="benefits-list">
          <li>Learn devious techniques for use in the (highly underrated) field of email marketing. <b>Preview: ever think of putting a large, useless button in the centre of your promotional emails, even when that button does nothing other than link to your homepage? </b>People love clicking on big, shiny buttons, and this is the basis of this practice. The text written on your giant, fake button can say anything at all, so make it enticing. For example, I once used a huge button that read, “Activate Discount” even though the reality was that the discount had already been activated by the server-side code before the email was ever sent.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="half-page">
        <h3>Conversion Optimisation</h3>
        <ul class="benefits-list">
          <li>High-level discussion of conversion optimisiation, focusing on the major leverage possibilities, i.e. reducing funnel length, <b>tweaking time variables, toying with pricing, minimising on-page clickables, constructing clever choice architecture, and directing user attention</b> through salience. Buying traffic is super expensive, so one of the most efficient things any online marketer can do is to squeeze more conversions out of the visitors they already have.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Copywriting</h3>
        <ul class="benefits-list">
          <li>What to say on your sales pages. The section on copywriting is the perfect antidote for anyone fighting the writer's block that accompanies the creation of landing pages. <b>Included are psychological tricks from the science of persuasion, practical measures inspired by behavioural economics, and copywriter-to-copywriter best-practices that are known to work.</b></li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Search Engine Optimisation</h3>
        <ul class="benefits-list">
          <li>The <b>internals of Google's mysterious Quality Score metric</b>, the magic metric that can dramatically reduce your cost of advertising once mastered.</li>
          <li>The various ways in which <b>rich snippets and structured data enhance your website's showing in Google Search results.</b> Judicious use of these markup technologies can greatly improve your "organic click-through rate". In English, this means that a higher percentage of people encountering your website in search results will end up clicking through to visit. If stiff competition prevents you from ranking #1 in Google Search results, it's often better to focus on getting more traffic from your <u>current</u> ranking position, even if you're stuck down at #8.</li>

          <li><b>The basics of white-hat (and gray-hat) Search Engine Optimisation, both on-site and off:</b> we'll cover everything from HTML title tags, to scalable content creation strategies, to techniques for attracting incoming links (e.g. Brian Dean's Skyscraper Technique). Content is still king in SEO, so the question becomes "how do you leverage human tendencies to verbalise or show off in generating compelling content at little expense?"</li>
          <li><b>The pitfalls of choosing the wrong domain or top-level domain (i.e. ".co.uk" or a ".com").</b> There are some serious gotchas that are essential to know <i>before</i> you launch your business. Not knowing these things could cost you tens or hundreds of thousands in lost earnings.</li>

          <li>The technical wizardly needed to <b>max out search engine benefit when your website architecture is complicated by subdomains, legacy URLs, regionalisations, duplicate pages, and foreign language translations.</b></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
</div>

