    <div class="objection-answers">
      <div id="objection-not-marketer">
        <p>
          Engineers often describe themselves as lacking the sales/marketing mindset. But this is defeatist thinking: marketing is not magic. It is not innate. It is not outside your reach. I would describe myself as "an <i>unnatural</i> born salesman", a math/music/programmer-type who studied sales/marketing later in life. I've found that the ever more technical aspects of modern marketing techniques are a good match for our engineering brains. All the slick haircuts and smooth-talking in the world won't help the classic "natural born salesperson" interpret analytical reports or navigate the maze of paid advertising targeting options or implement scalable SEO strategies.
        </p>
        <p>Furthermore, there are no pre-requisites required for this book: it is designed to be readable even by people without any online marketing experience. You don't need any familiarity with the alphabet soup of acronyms (CPC, PPC, CTR, SEO etc.). Nor do you need to have ever marketed before.</p>
      </div>
      <div id="objection-too-expensive" class="hidden">
        <p>Buying this book is an investment in your education, in your future wealth. People routinely spend $10,000+ on college fees and accompanying living expenses, even though today's job market means that the financial return on investment for many courses is dwindling. That said, there are few skills that are as great a financial force-multiplier today as online marketing. The handful of dollars you spend today could earn you tens (or even hundreds) of thousands tomorrow.</p>
        <p>Learning about online marketing before getting your feet wet is a soft of insurance policy. Think about it: online marketing campaigns cost money to run—that much is unavoidable. If you create an amateur Google AdWords campaign, you are going to burn through your cash like nobody's business. There is an enormous cost to diving into online marketing blind. By investing in this book, you can insure yourself against some of the gravest and most expensive future mistakes.
          <p>"If You Pay Peanuts, You'll Get Monkeys": that is a saying from commercial life that I've found to be true time and time again (e.g. when hiring seemingly cheap outsourced programmers only to realise they were dangerously incompetent.) Do you want to read a 400-word blog post by some self-styled "social media mogul" or would you prefer to read a carefully written book authored by a law graduate-cum-programmer-cum-entrepreneur, from someone who has built a real business? <i><%= book.title %></i> is not your typical e-book thrown together unprofessionally in 24 hours; rather, it is a serious work which was created over 18 months with the help of a team of professionals over four rounds of edits. TL;DR: it cost a pretty penny to throw this together for you and we're charging that it's worth.
          </p>
          <p>Are you a business or freelancer or student? In many tax jurisdictions, you can offset the price of this book against your tax bill.</p>
          <p>Last but not least, if the book's price were lower you wouldn't read it. Paying money for something creates an internal obligation to use and apply it. #gym-membership-effect</p>
      </div>
      <div id="objection-free-blog" class="hidden">
        <p>In the years preceding the writing of this book, I assembled an elite group of successful online marketers and regularly met with them to exchange tactics. Among these were multiple ex-Google employees, the owner of a consultancy that did conversion optimisation for Amazon, the AdWords guy for Goldman Sachs, a Serbian making $100,000 a month selling e-books on dating, an affiliate marketer turned top-10 bestselling author, the heads of marketing for Delivery Hero, Research Gate, and Contentful, and an impossibly intelligent, quite possibly immortal, and most certainly immoral Taiwanese man named Ulysses. I gathered these strategies and techniques–some of which the original authors couldn't attach their names to in public–and made them all available to you in anonymised form as part of their public premiere.</p>

        <p>Because I came from a nerdy, programmer background, I like to arrange concepts and ideas neatly. I worked for a year-and-a-half to impose structure and order on the chaotic, rapidly changing field that is internet marketing. The end result of this focus is a book that connects the dots together and helps you see the big principles with the eyes of an experienced expert. Compare this to reading a blog that was written article-by-article, where in each post the author tears off only a tiny piece of reality and deals with it in isolation. By writing in such a piecemeal fashion without an overarching plan, the blog author often doesn't realise that what they say today is inconsistent with what they said yesterday, making for a frustrating and unsatisfying read.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</div>
